==English==
===Proper noun===
{{wikipedia}}
'''Rosicrucian'''
# the term used to designate the 'Brothers' of the 'Order of the Rose Cross': Rosicrucian(s), Rosicrucian Order. It was originally employed in the three Manifestos of the Order, published as anonymous in the early 17th century: ''Fama Fraternitatis'', 1614; ''Confessio Fraternitatis'', 1615; and ''The Chymical Wedding of Christian Rosenkreuz'', 1616.
'''Rosicrucianist'''
#a member of any modern group or organization formed for the study of Rosicrucianism and allied subjects (eg.: ''The Rosicrucian Fellowship''). However, the members of some modern groups designate themselves as Rosicrucians (eg.: the ''Ancient Mystic Order Rosae Crucis'').

===Proper adjective===
'''Rosicrucian'''
# applied to designate [[mystic]], [[occult]] or [[esoteric]] philosophy teachings related to Rosicrucianism.